article.headline: Houston 69, Tulsa 67
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Houston weathered a furious Tulsa comeback, including a potential game-winning 3-point attempt by Charles Ramsdell at the buzzer, for a 69-67 victory on Saturday. Houston (7-9, 2-2 Conference USA) snapped a 15-game home winning streak by Tulsa (12-5, 2-2). Dion Dowell scored 21 points and Robert McKiver added 20 for Houston. Those two combined to make 10 3-pointers, including 5-of-8 by Dowell. Their outside shooting prowess kept Tulsa at bay for most of the contest, as the Cougars led throughout, had a 33-27 halftime lead and a 65-56 advantage with 1:16 to play. Darold Crow started the Tulsa comeback with a 3-pointer with 1:02 left. After two missed free throws by Houston, Ben Uzoh drove for a basket. Oliver LaFayette made one free throw for the Cougars, then Rod Earls nailed a 3-pointer for Tulsa to close within 66-64 with 27 seconds left. After Oliver made two free throws, Uzoh hit another trey from the right corner as Tulsa closed within 68-67 with 8.7 seconds left. McKiver made 1-of-2 free throws with 7.3 seconds left before Uzoh brought the ball up and gave it to Ramsdell, but the 3-pointer by the 6-foot-10 senior was off the mark. Oliver and Jahmar Thorpe scored 13 points each for Houston. Uzoh led Tulsa with 18 points, followed by Ramsdell with 13 points and 10 rebounds and Ray Reese with 11 points. Tulsa pounded Houston on the boards 46-22 but had 17 turnovers to just seven for the Cougars. Tulsa also cost itself at the free-throw line, making just 15 of 24. Tulsa shot 42.3 percent from the field while Houston wasn't much better at 43.4 percent. The Cougars did make five of their first six 3-point attempts in the second half to extend their lead to 50-38.
